  "source": {
    "whest": "https://github.com/AIcrowd/whest/blob/main/src/whest/_pointwise.py#L1090-L1098",
    "numpy": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.corrcoef.html"
  },
  "op": {
    "name": "corrcoef",
    "module": "numpy",
    "whest_ref": "we.corrcoef",
    "numpy_ref": "np.corrcoef",
    "category": "counted_custom",
    "status": "supported",
    "weight": 1.0,
    "cost_formula": "n^2 * m",
    "cost_formula_latex": "$n^2 \\cdot m$",
    "notes": "Pearson correlation coefficients.",
    "summary": "Return Pearson product-moment correlation coefficients.",
    "signature": "we.corrcoef(x, y=None, rowvar=True, bias=<no value>, ddof=<no value>, *, dtype=None)"
  },
  "docs": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "kind": "summary",
        "title": "Summary",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Return Pearson product-moment correlation coefficients."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Please refer to the documentation for `cov` for more detail.  The\nrelationship between the correlation coefficient matrix, `R`, and the\ncovariance matrix, `C`, is"
          },
          {
            "type": "directive",
            "name": "math:: R_{ij} = \\frac{ C_{ij} } { \\sqrt{ C_{ii} C_{jj} } }",
            "body": "",
            "raw": ".. math:: R_{ij} = \\frac{ C_{ij} } { \\sqrt{ C_{ii} C_{jj} } }"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "The values of `R` are between -1 and 1, inclusive."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "parameters",
        "title": "Parameters",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "x",
            "type": "array_like",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "A 1-D or 2-D array containing multiple variables and observations.\nEach row of `x` represents a variable, and each column a single\nobservation of all those variables. Also see `rowvar` below."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "y",
            "type": "array_like, optional",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "An additional set of variables and observations. `y` has the same\nshape as `x`."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "rowvar",
            "type": "bool, optional",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "If `rowvar` is True (default), then each row represents a\nvariable, with observations in the columns. Otherwise, the relationship\nis transposed: each column represents a variable, while the rows\ncontain observations."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "bias",
            "type": "_NoValue, optional",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "Has no effect, do not use."
              },
              {
                "type": "directive",
                "name": "deprecated:: 1.10.0",
                "body": "",
                "raw": ".. deprecated:: 1.10.0"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "ddof",
            "type": "_NoValue, optional",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "Has no effect, do not use."
              },
              {
                "type": "directive",
                "name": "deprecated:: 1.10.0",
                "body": "",
                "raw": ".. deprecated:: 1.10.0"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "dtype",
            "type": "data-type, optional",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "Data-type of the result. By default, the return data-type will have\nat least `numpy.float64` precision."
              },
              {
                "type": "directive",
                "name": "versionadded:: 1.20",
                "body": "",
                "raw": ".. versionadded:: 1.20"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "returns",
        "title": "Returns",
        "items": [
          {
            "name": "R",
            "type": "ndarray",
            "desc_blocks": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "text": "The correlation coefficient matrix of the variables."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "notes",
        "title": "Notes",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Due to floating point rounding the resulting array may not be Hermitian,\nthe diagonal elements may not be 1, and the elements may not satisfy the\ninequality abs(a) <= 1. The real and imaginary parts are clipped to the\ninterval [-1,  1] in an attempt to improve on that situation but is not\nmuch help in the complex case."
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "This function accepts but discards arguments `bias` and `ddof`.  This is\nfor backwards compatibility with previous versions of this function.  These\narguments had no effect on the return values of the function and can be\nsafely ignored in this and previous versions of numpy."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "kind": "examples",
        "title": "Examples",
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> import numpy as np"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "In this example we generate two random arrays, ``xarr`` and ``yarr``, and\ncompute the row-wise and column-wise Pearson correlation coefficients,\n``R``. Since ``rowvar`` is  true by  default, we first find the row-wise\nPearson correlation coefficients between the variables of ``xarr``."
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> import numpy as np\n>>> rng = np.random.default_rng(seed=42)\n>>> xarr = rng.random((3, 3))\n>>> xarr\narray([[0.77395605, 0.43887844, 0.85859792],\n       [0.69736803, 0.09417735, 0.97562235],\n       [0.7611397 , 0.78606431, 0.12811363]])\n>>> R1 = np.corrcoef(xarr)\n>>> R1\narray([[ 1.        ,  0.99256089, -0.68080986],\n       [ 0.99256089,  1.        , -0.76492172],\n       [-0.68080986, -0.76492172,  1.        ]])"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "If we add another set of variables and observations ``yarr``, we can\ncompute the row-wise Pearson correlation coefficients between the\nvariables in ``xarr`` and ``yarr``."
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> yarr = rng.random((3, 3))\n>>> yarr\narray([[0.45038594, 0.37079802, 0.92676499],\n       [0.64386512, 0.82276161, 0.4434142 ],\n       [0.22723872, 0.55458479, 0.06381726]])\n>>> R2 = np.corrcoef(xarr, yarr)\n>>> R2\narray([[ 1.        ,  0.99256089, -0.68080986,  0.75008178, -0.934284  ,\n        -0.99004057],\n       [ 0.99256089,  1.        , -0.76492172,  0.82502011, -0.97074098,\n        -0.99981569],\n       [-0.68080986, -0.76492172,  1.        , -0.99507202,  0.89721355,\n         0.77714685],\n       [ 0.75008178,  0.82502011, -0.99507202,  1.        , -0.93657855,\n        -0.83571711],\n       [-0.934284  , -0.97074098,  0.89721355, -0.93657855,  1.        ,\n         0.97517215],\n       [-0.99004057, -0.99981569,  0.77714685, -0.83571711,  0.97517215,\n         1.        ]])"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "text": "Finally if we use the option ``rowvar=False``, the columns are now\nbeing treated as the variables and we will find the column-wise Pearson\ncorrelation coefficients between variables in ``xarr`` and ``yarr``."
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "language": "text",
            "code": ">>> R3 = np.corrcoef(xarr, yarr, rowvar=False)\n>>> R3\narray([[ 1.        ,  0.77598074, -0.47458546, -0.75078643, -0.9665554 ,\n         0.22423734],\n       [ 0.77598074,  1.        , -0.92346708, -0.99923895, -0.58826587,\n        -0.44069024],\n       [-0.47458546, -0.92346708,  1.        ,  0.93773029,  0.23297648,\n         0.75137473],\n       [-0.75078643, -0.99923895,  0.93773029,  1.        ,  0.55627469,\n         0.47536961],\n       [-0.9665554 , -0.58826587,  0.23297648,  0.55627469,  1.        ,\n        -0.46666491],\n       [ 0.22423734, -0.44069024,  0.75137473,  0.47536961, -0.46666491,\n         1.        ]])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
